# Topic 34: Schema Enforcement ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

## Why was Schema Enforcement introduced?

Suppose your table is

```
ID
Name
Salary
```

Someone loads

```
ID
Name
Age
```

Without validation,

your data becomes inconsistent.

---

## Concept

**Schema Enforcement** ensures that incoming data **matches the existing table schema**.

> **Simple Definition:** Prevents invalid data from entering a table.

---

## Theory

Existing Table

```
ID
Name
Salary
```

Incoming Data

```
ID
Name
Age
```

Delta rejects the write.

---

## Architecture

```text
Incoming Data
      │
      ▼
Schema Validation
      │
 ┌────┴────┐
 │         │
Valid    Invalid
 │         │
 ▼         ▼
Write    Reject
```

---

## Syntax

```python
df.write.format("delta").save("/delta/sales")
```

If schema doesn't match,

Spark throws an error.

---

## Real Example

Customers table

```
CustomerID
Name
City
```

Someone uploads

```
CustomerID
Phone
```

Delta rejects it.

---

## Interview Questions

### What is Schema Enforcement?

Validation that prevents incorrect schemas from being written.

---

### Why is it important?

Maintains data quality.

---

### Does Delta automatically allow new columns?

No.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Thinking Delta automatically accepts schema changes.

---

# Topic 35: Schema Evolution ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

## Why was Schema Evolution introduced?

Business requirements change.

Old schema

```
EmployeeID
Name
Salary
```

New requirement

```
EmployeeID
Name
Salary
Department
```

Without Schema Evolution,

the write fails.

---

## Concept

**Schema Evolution** allows Delta Lake to **add compatible schema changes** automatically.

> **Simple Definition:** Allows tables to grow when the schema changes.

---

## Theory

Old Schema

```
ID
Name
```

New Data

```
ID
Name
Email
```

Enable Schema Evolution

↓

New Table

```
ID
Name
Email
```

---

## Architecture

```text
Incoming Data
      │
      ▼
New Column?
      │
 ┌────┴────┐
 │         │
 No       Yes
 │         │
 ▼         ▼
Write   Update Schema
            │
            ▼
          Write
```

---

## Syntax

```python
df.write \
.option("mergeSchema","true") \
.format("delta") \
.mode("append") \
.save("/delta/employees")
```

---

## Real Example

Yesterday

```
ID
Name
```

Today

```
ID
Name
Email
```

With

```python
mergeSchema=true
```

Delta automatically adds **Email**.

---

## Interview Questions

### What is Schema Evolution?

Automatically updating the table schema to include compatible new columns.

---

### Difference between Schema Enforcement and Schema Evolution?

* **Enforcement** → Rejects schema mismatch.
* **Evolution** → Allows compatible schema changes.

---

### Which option enables Schema Evolution?

```python
mergeSchema=true
```

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Confusing Schema Enforcement with Schema Evolution.

❌ Assuming all schema changes are allowed (incompatible changes may still fail).

---

# ⭐ Interview Cheat Sheet

| Topic              | One-line Answer                                            |
| ------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| Time Travel        | Read previous versions of a Delta table.                   |
| Schema Enforcement | Rejects invalid schema writes.                             |
| Schema Evolution   | Allows compatible schema changes using `mergeSchema=true`. |

---

# 🎯 Most Asked Interview Question

### Q: Difference between Schema Enforcement and Schema Evolution?

| Schema Enforcement      | Schema Evolution                        |
| ----------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Validates schema        | Updates schema                          |
| Rejects mismatched data | Adds compatible new columns             |
| Default behavior        | Requires `mergeSchema=true`             |
| Improves data quality   | Supports changing business requirements |

